%S A085308 0,2,3,2,5,2,7,2,3,1,11,2,13,2,53,2,17,2,19,1,73,2,23,2,5,1,3,2,29,1,
%T A085308 31,2,113,2,53,2,37,2,197,1,41,1,43,2,53,1,47,2,7,1,173,1,53,2,41113,
%U A085308 2,193,1,59,1,61,1,73,2,53,1,67,2,233,1,71,2,73,1,53,2,197,1,79,1,3,1,83,1,53
%N A085308 Iterate function described in A085307 (= reverse concatenation of prime factors); a(n) is either (i) the fixed point [=prime] if it exists, (ii) a(n)=1 if no convergence occurs (most even initial values); (iii) a(n)=0 if n=1 or if the iteration results in a nontrivial cycle.
%C A085308 Algorithm (for each step of the iteration):
%C A085308 1. factorize n;
%C A085308 2. arrange prime factors by decreasing size;
%C A085308 3. concatenate prime factors and interpret the result as a decimal number.
%e A085308 n=even: remains even: m = 100 = 2*2*5*5 -> {2,5} -> {5,2} -> 52 = a(100).
%e A085308 If n = 2^i*3^j, then a(n)=2 since iteration list is {n,32,2}; these are the known convergent even cases of initial value.
%e A085308 n=143: a(143) = 44864859110711 because the iteration list is {143, 1311, 23193, 8593, 66113, 388917, 547793, 2273241, 55311373, 989474313, 8914183373, 84859143973, 528059391607, 44864859110711}.
%e A085308 a(n) = 0 for n = 213, 323, 639, 713 ending in {713, 3123, 3473, 15123}; a cycle of length = 4.
%e A085308 All possible cases occur: fixed point, divergence, terminal cycle.
%Y A085308 Cf. A084317-A084319, A085307, A085309.
%K A085308 base,nonn
%O A085308 1,2
%A A085308 _Labos Elemer_, Jun 27 2003
%E A085308 Edited and corrected by _Sean A. Irvine_, Jun 13 2026
